# Jujutsu Revsets - Quick Reference

A concise guide to Jujutsu's revset language for selecting commits.

## Symbols

| Symbol | Meaning |
|--------|---------|
| `@` | Working copy commit |
| `workspace@` | Working copy in another workspace |
| `name@remote` | Remote-tracking bookmark |
| `abc123` | Commit ID (full or unique prefix) |
| `xyz` | Change ID (full or unique prefix) |

## Core Operators

| Operator | Description | Example |
|----------|-------------|---------|
| `x-` | Parents of x | `@-` (parent of working copy) |
| `x+` | Children of x | `@+` (children of working copy) |
| `::x` | Ancestors of x (including x) | `::@` (all ancestors to working copy) |
| `x::` | Descendants of x (including x) | `@::` (working copy and descendants) |
| `..x` | Ancestors of x (excluding root) | `..@` |
| `x..` | Non-ancestors of x | `main..` (commits not on main) |
| `x::y` | Path from x to y | `main::@` (ancestry path) |
| `x..y` | Commits in y but not x | `main..@` (commits ahead of main) |
| `~x` | Not in x | `~main` (everything except main) |
| `x & y` | In both x and y | `@- & main` |
| `x \| y` | In either x or y | `@- \| main` |

## Essential Functions

### Navigation
- `parents(x)` / `x-` - Parents
- `children(x)` / `x+` - Children
- `ancestors(x)` / `::x` - All ancestors
- `descendants(x)` / `x::` - All descendants

### Sets
- `all()` - All visible commits
- `none()` - Empty set
- `heads(x)` - Commits in x with no children in x
- `roots(x)` - Commits in x with no parents in x
- `latest(x, count)` - Most recent commits in x

### References
- `bookmarks()` - All local bookmarks
- `remote_bookmarks()` - All remote bookmarks
- `tags()` - All tags
- `trunk()` - Main branch (origin/main, master, etc.)

### Content Search
- `description(pattern)` - Commits matching description
- `subject(pattern)` - Commits matching first line
- `author(pattern)` - Commits by author
- `files(path)` - Commits modifying files
- `empty()` - Commits with no changes

### State
- `mine()` - Commits authored by current user
- `merges()` - Merge commits
- `conflicts()` - Commits with conflicts

## Common Patterns

### Basic Navigation
```shell
# Show working copy parent
jj log -r @-

# Show all ancestors (like git log)
jj log -r ::@

# Show recent commits
jj log -r latest(all(), 10)
```

### Branch Management
```shell
# Commits not on any remote
jj log -r 'remote_bookmarks()..'

# Commits ahead of main
jj log -r 'main..@'

# Local commits and their descendants
jj log -r '(remote_bookmarks()..@)::'
```

### Search and Filter
```shell
# My commits
jj log -r mine()

# Commits with "fix" in description
jj log -r 'description(fix)'

# Empty commits
jj log -r empty()

# Merge commits
jj log -r merges()
```

### Complex Queries
```shell
# My commits not on main
jj log -r 'mine() & main..'

# Important commits (tags and bookmarks)
jj log -r 'tags() | bookmarks()'

# Commits by author containing keyword
jj log -r 'author(john) & description(bugfix)'
```

## String Patterns

| Pattern | Description | Example |
|---------|-------------|---------|
| `"text"` | Contains text | `description("fix bug")` |
| `exact:"text"` | Exact match | `subject(exact:"Initial commit")` |
| `glob:"pattern"` | Shell wildcards | `author(glob:"*@company.com")` |
| `regex:"pattern"` | Regular expression | `description(regex:"fix(es)?")` |

Add `-i` suffix for case-insensitive matching: `glob-i:"fix*"`

## Date Patterns

```shell
# Commits after date
author_date(after:"2024-01-01")

# Commits before date
committer_date(before:"yesterday")

# Recent commits
author_date(after:"1 week ago")
```

## Useful Aliases

Add to your config file:
```toml
[revset-aliases]
'HEAD' = '@-'
'mine' = 'mine()'
'recent' = 'latest(all(), 20)'
'wip' = 'description(regex:"^(wip|WIP|temp)")'
```

## Pro Tips

1. Use `present(x)` to avoid errors with non-existent refs
2. The `all:` modifier allows large revsets: `jj rebase -d all:main+`
3. Combine operators: `(main..@) & mine()` for your commits ahead of main
4. Use parentheses for complex expressions: `(x & y) | z`
5. Quote symbols with special chars: `"feature-branch"`